reviewText: Can't wait to see what extras are on the DVD. Saw the HBO special several times and loved it, got funnier every time. Like some of the greats, Carlin, Pryor and so on he is able to make his vulgarity work for him so that he doesn't sound like so many other comics, just being vulgar and offensive for the sheer shock of it. It comes across as natural, as if it is just who he is and how he sees the world. No one is safe from ridicule, even himself. I can't recommend this special enough. One of the freshest minds in comedy since Eddie Izzard.

Best parts were the first 3/4. The last 15 minutes descended into him talking about putting things up his rectum - not exactly "comedy".  Before that, he was on a roll!  Funny, perhaps unusual (aka not "mainstream"), good perception, funny and irreverent.  After the 3/4 mark, I would probably just turn it off.

I decided to check out "I Swear to God" because, out of all the comics interviewed in the mostly monotonous Misery Loves Comedy, Jim Jefferies seemed to have some of the funniest responses. Sadly, I saw little evidence of that originality here.

"I Swear to God" leans hard on stand-up stand-bys--sex, drugs, fat people, religion, rape, foreigners--Jefferies' takes on these topics are as formulaic as the set list.  Even when a joke's set-up calls attention to a particular comedic convention ("Every comic who has a Muslim joke does a terrorist joke"), he makes no effort to take it in a different direction ("You take bacon and beer away from me, and I'd fly a plane into a building, too"). The vignettes drawn from his personal experience seem more promising, but eventually they disintegrate into stock characters and situations, too.

I will freely admit that I prefer comedy that "punches up" more than "punching down," but the best comedians seem to find ways of using this sort of self-righteous indignation to their advantage--revealing that a joke they've just told is only offensive if you were making certain stereotypical assumptions to start with, for instance. Jefferies seems to take the exact opposite approach: his bits develop exactly the way you expect them to, with very few surprises. After the first half, I started jumping around to see if the set got any more interesting, and ended up turning it off early--not because I was offended, but because I was falling asleep.

If you begin this special and quit after three or four minutes, because its too offensive, then you are a child unable to handle grown up themes. Watch this special all the way through, and you will laugh until you cant breathe. Jim Jefferies begins with his routine with a few self-depreciation jokes and ends with a hilarious story about an exciting trip to Amsterdam; between these two parts, he jokes about the absurdity of religion, the banality of sex, the horror of life, and his dysfunctional family. A must see for any fans of comedy or for any human being.

on the front half of his show, jeffries brought something very fresh to standup.  he explored Christianity, believing in God, our need for an afterlife, and so forth with great panache and style.  I just loved this part of the show and I applaud him for it.  He moved on from there to his family, which I also really enjoyed. However, for the back half of the show he explored sex and bathroom humor, which included one long story about removing an egg from his rectum.  Sex and bathroom humor sells but I am really tired of it.  There is almost nothing new you can do here.  His trip to the porn warehouse was somewhat amusing since I didn't know there was such a place.  However, his real strength is his standup about religion and his family (mother, father, brother with its Australian accent since that is where they are all located).  If he stuck to those two, he would have an incredibly fresh and original show.  the first half of the show is five stars so it is well worth watching that.  the back half is at best three stars and for me personally, considerably less.

Jim Jefferies, or Jeffries, as he prefers to use as his stage name, is one of the hottest, funniest comedians performing today. His style of humor is confrontative, "angry man," and very profane. He is an Aussie, and Aussies like to swear and curse like drunken sailors. If you are sensitive to use of the f-word, this is not your kind of comedy. His subjects range from religion, gays and lesbians, ethnic groups, to his own family. But, all his stories are laced with profanities, and probably would gross out more sensitive viewers. I personally love his comedic style and timing, and highly recommend this video to those who are fans of George Carlin and similar comedians.

For those of you wondering what it's about...the best way I can describe it is a schmorgesborg of self-deprecation and religion/panda bashing mixed with a lot of profanity.  If that interests you, then don't hesitate...buy this now.

I had a difficult time understanding what this Australian-born buffoon was saying from the first time he opened his profanity-stained mouth. But I did understand him well enough to hear him openly profess that he is an atheist who arrogantly believes that he is right and everyone else is wrong about there being no God (despite the lingering fact that the non-existence of God has never been proven). At this point, I became very grateful that there were no English subtitles on this DVD since I had no interest in listening to anything else that this dimwitted dunderhead from down under had to say. It was not his being an atheist in and of itself that turned me off so much as his close-minded view that everyone else (like me) who does believe in God is wrong. I have learned to respect the inalienable right of others to believe or not believe in the unseen realities of the spiritual world. I have no interest in turning any hardcore atheist into a spiritual-minded God-knowing truth-seeker but neither will I tolerate listening to any material-minded God-rejecting truth-hater who might be attempting to convert me from monotheism to atheism (especially if this non-believing atheist is a so-called comedian who uses the stage to propagate his anti-God sentiments)! There is just nothing funny about atheistic propaganda. The last thing I heard him say before I merrily clicked on my remote's STOP button to silence this funny little man's pessimistic propaganda forever (at least as far as the realm of my consciousness is concerned) was something about how when we die, there is nothing that happens after that. Perhaps for the non-believing atheist, such a vapid view shall become a self-fulfilling prophecy. I'd rather spend eternity trying to unravel the perplexing mysteries of a God of Love who has invited all of His time-space kids to share an endless journey of discovery and adventure with Him as opposed to being a gutless coward who surrenders to the final sleep of death.

Jefferies has definitely listened to plenty of Bill Hicks' religious material, but adds his own gleefully misogynistic take on things while drinking four pints of lager as the show progresses. All in the name of a good time, mind you, though Jim confesses that he's always hated life and found it dull and pointless. Good start for a comedian!

He seems to have a pretty good time though, even when discussing his lack of endowment down under. His Aussie roots are clear enough from his bashing of the Sheila sub-species, but he's likeable enough to not offend.

He drops the f's constantly, so beware, and if you're easily offended, this will easily offend. But it's worth watching for any fans of honest comedy and uninhibited wrath at all and sundry. There's plenty of truth here, however uncomfortable, and that's always a good thing.
